snippet.textDisplay: A gaming Mac would be great (at least for me). But, Apple will never support the open technologies required to be competitive with Windows, though. Just look at the long history between Apple and OpenGL. The only saving grace here would be some sort of Vulcan layer that communicates with Metal 2. Another issue is going to be drivers and GPU support (read: Apple and Nvidia). If they release an all-in-one for gaming, its definitely DOA. The only thing that makes sense here would be for Apple to introduce a gaming focused Mac Pro that is fully upgradeable and compatible with DX, Vulcan and Metal, as well as Nvidia. But macOS + virtually all Windows games? I'd definitely buy if they do it right; won't be holding my breath though.
snippet.textOriginal: A gaming Mac would be great (at least for me). But, Apple will never support the open technologies required to be competitive with Windows, though. Just look at the long history between Apple and OpenGL. The only saving grace here would be some sort of Vulcan layer that communicates with Metal 2. Another issue is going to be drivers and GPU support (read: Apple and Nvidia). If they release an all-in-one for gaming, its definitely DOA. The only thing that makes sense here would be for Apple to introduce a gaming focused Mac Pro that is fully upgradeable and compatible with DX, Vulcan and Metal, as well as Nvidia. But macOS + virtually all Windows games? I'd definitely buy if they do it right; won't be holding my breath though.
